gues that while Jewish religious and cultural distinctiveness might have remained unquestioned in this late Ottoman port city, other elements of Jewish identity emerged as profound sites of tension, most notably those of poverty and social class. Through the voices of both beggars on the street and mercantile elites, shoe-shiners and newspaper editors, rabbis and housewives, this book argues that it was new attitudes to poverty and class, not Judaism, that most significantly framed this Sephardi community's encounter with the modern age.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aJewszTurkeyzİzmirxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszTurkeyzİzmirxHistoryy20th century. 0aJewszTurkeyzİzmirxHistoryy19th century. 0aJewszTurkeyzİzmirxHistoryy20th century. 0aSephardimzTurkeyzİzmirxEconomic conditions. 0aSephardimzTurkeyzİzmirxHistory. 0aSephardimzTurkeyzİzmirxSocial conditions. 0aSephardimzTurkeyzİzmirxEconomic conditions. 0aSephardimzTurkeyzİzmirxHistory. 0aSephardimzTurkeyzİzmirxSocial conditions. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aOttoman Izmir.  aSephardi Jewry.  amodernity.  apoverty.  asocial class.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020 Englishz978311070477808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Theol., Relig.Stud., Jewish Stud. 2020z9783110704570oZDB-23-DGF08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Frontlist eBook-Package 2020z978311069218140uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150361092740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503610927423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover